<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="31">
These leaf-cutting ants are represented in California by a single species, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24768" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex versicolor (Pergande)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="versicolor">Acromyrmex versicolor(Pergande)</taxonomicName>
, confined to the southern deserts. The harvested leaves are used to culture a basidiomycete fungus, which is the principal food of the ants. References: Gamboa (1975, 1976), Johnson and Rissing (1993), Julian and Fewell (2004), Mueller et al. (2001), Reichardt and Wheeler (1996), Rissing et al. (1986, 1989), Snelling and George (1979), Weber (1972).
</paragraph>
